  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT109-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">ciṟaippuṟam. tam vēṟupāṭu kaṇṭa puṟattār alar kūṟukiṉṟamai tōṉṟat tōḻi talaimakaṭkuk kūṟuvāḷāyk kūṟiyatu. (C5: ciṟaippuṟam.)</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Hedge. Spoken as if speaking to HER by the confidante so that [HE] would realise the gossip spoken by outsiders who had seen the changes in her.</p>
          </div>
          


        <div xml:id="KT109">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                muṭakkā liṟaviṉ muṭaṅkupuṟap peruṅkiḷai</l>
<l>                puṇari yikutirai tarūun tuṟaivaṉ</l>
<l>                puṇariya virunta ñāṉṟu</l>
<l>                miṉṉatu maṉṉō naṉṉutaṟ kaviṉē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
           <l rend="indent">Each time the man from the ghat, where breaking ocean waves</l>
           <l rend="indent">yield<note place="foot">For the gift of the waters cf. KT 90.5: ... <term xml:lang="ta">aruvi uṇ tuṟai tarūum / kuṉṟa nāṭaṉ</term>.</note> big bent-backed hordes of bent-legged prawns,</l>
           <l rend="indent">has been there to unite with [you/her],</l>
           <l>such [is] surely the good forehead's beauty?<note place="foot">Here we have to read an elliptical crossing of the levels of statement: HER good forehead no longer clear is the white beach littered with prawn.</note></l>
           <lg type="alternate" resp="#TVG" sameAs="4b">
            <l>[is] such, alas, the good forehead's beauty<note place="foot">Thus the traditional interpretation which, however, completely ignores the <term xml:lang="ta">-ō</term> and needs an additional meaning of <term xml:lang="ta">maṉ</term> (which is, to be sure, backed up by the Tol. Col. 254).</note></l>
           </lg>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
